            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The Welsh Corpus notes that <q>The inscription is probably incomplete, the top edge of the stone and the upper part of the right-hand edge not being present</q>(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 255). The length of spacing between the legible letters suggests that the vowels between them may be A O or U but they could also be E or I. <q>Rhys (1896) and Nash-Williams(1950) read [the inscription] as 'Gluvoca'</q>(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 255; Rhys 1879; Nash-Williams 1950). The fourth letter in the inscription may be a V but <q>close examination of the ogam suggests a fourth horizontal stroke from the bottom which has clearly been truncated by the circle around the cross. This confirms that the cross is later than the ogam inscription </q>(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 256. A fourth horizontal stroke would make the character as S but the Welsh Corpus also notes that <q>if a fifth stroke had also been removed this would give an N</q>(Redknap and Lewis 2007, 255).</p>            
            </div>
